28 A grant agreement may obligate the State to make a series of grant payments over a period
29 of up to 10 years. Nothing in this section constitutes or authorizes a guarantee or assumption by
30 the State of any debt of any business or authorizes the taxing power or the full faith and credit of
31 the State to be pledged.
32 The Department shall cooperate with the Attorney General's office in preparing the
33 documentation for the grant agreement. The Attorney General shall review the terms of all
34 proposed agreements to be entered into under this section. To be effective against the State, an
35 agreement entered into under this section shall be signed personally by the Attorney General.
36 (k) Safeguards. – To ensure that public funds are used only to carry out the public
37 purposes provided in this section, the Department shall require that each business that receives a
38 grant under this section shall agree to meet performance criteria to protect the State's investment
39 and ensure that the projected benefits of the project are secured. The performance criteria to be
40 required shall include maintenance of an appropriate level of employment at specified levels of
41 compensation, compensation for required levels of employment, maintenance of health insurance
42 for all full-time employees, investment of a specified amount over the term of the agreement, and
43 any other criteria the Department considers appropriate. The agreement shall require the business
44 to repay or reimburse an appropriate portion of the grant based on the extent of any failure by the
45 business to meet the performance criteria. The agreement shall require the business to repay all
46 amounts received under the agreement and to forfeit any future grant payments if the business
47 fails to satisfy the investment eligibility requirement of this section. The use of contract
48 employees shall not be used to reduce compensation at the project that is the subject of the
49 agreement.
